    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-08-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-08-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="695"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d695">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/6451</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The French Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_JJJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jusserand</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-08-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 11, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 14.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: My Government informs me that
                    it has received from our Consul at Monrovia a report to the effect that the
                    Liberian Government expressed a wish that the German Consul, the German
                    Receiver, and the German women and children be put as early as possible on an
                    English or Spanish steamer bound for England, whence they would proceed to
                    Germany by way of a Scandinavian country.</p>
                <p>The answer to Mr. <persName>Baret</persName> was that there was no objection to
                    that arrangement on the part of the Government of the Republic, but that he
                    should concert with his American and English colleagues. It should further be
                    understood that the steamer will not call at the Spanish port where those
                    Germans could not easily be prevented from landing and staying.</p>
                <p>I have the honor to bring the foregoing to your excellency’s knowledge for all
                    pertinent purposes.</p>
                <p>Be pleased to accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JJJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jusserand</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
